Write a program to reverse the second half of a given number.

If the number has:

Odd digits → Keep the middle digit fixed and reverse the part after it.

Even digits → Reverse the second half of the number.

Input Format

A single integer n representing the number.

Constraints

1 ≤ n ≤ 10^9 The number should not have leading zeros.

Output Format

Print the integer obtained after reversing the second half of the digits of the given number.

Sample Input 0

12345
Sample Output 0

12543
Sample Input 1

123456
Sample Output 1

123654

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <math.h>
#include <stdlib.h>


int main() {
    int n;
    scanf("%d", &n);

    int temp = n, digits = 0;
    while (temp > 0) {
        digits++;
        temp /= 10;
    }

    // For odd digits, include the middle digit in the second half
    int half = digits / 2;
    if (digits % 2 != 0) {
        half = half + 1;   // push the middle digit into the second half
    }

    int divisor = (int)pow(10, half);

    int firstHalf = n / divisor;           // digits before the second half
    int secondHalf = n % divisor;          // second half (middle included if odd)

    // reverse the second half
    int rev = 0;
    while (secondHalf > 0) {
        rev = rev * 10 + (secondHalf % 10);
        secondHalf /= 10;
    }

    // recombine
    int result = firstHalf * divisor + rev;

    printf("%d\n", result);
    return 0;
}

